        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Layer and cook",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 150 degrees C fan. Melt the butter in a large casserole over medium heat. Add the red onion and cook for 5 minutes until soft.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the shredded cabbage, Bramley apple, sugar, vinegar, cloves, cinnamon, allspice, and bay leaf. Stir well to combine.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Cover tightly and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "braise",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp5pp2dg0000jcv4mbsuedx3"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " in the oven for 2 hours, stirring once or twice, until the cabbage is very tender and the liquid has reduced to a sticky glaze.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Remove the bay leaf and whole cloves. Taste and adjust: add more sugar if too sharp, more vinegar if too sweet.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Make sure the casserole has a tight-fitting lid. Add a sheet of greaseproof paper under the lid if it is loose. Cook for another 30 minutes.",
                "cause": "The lid was not tight enough, letting steam escape, or the oven was too cool.",
                "symptom": "Cabbage is still crunchy after 2 hours"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Add a splash more red wine vinegar and stir. Taste again; the balance should be sweet with a bright acidic edge.",
                "cause": "The Bramley apples were small, or the sugar was generous.",
                "symptom": "Too sweet"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Stir in a teaspoon more dark brown sugar. Let it melt in before tasting again.",
                "cause": "The vinegar was strong, or the apples were very tart.",
                "symptom": "Too sharp"
              },
              {
                "fix": "The vinegar fixes the colour. Always include it. The covered pot also helps preserve the deep red.",
                "cause": "The vinegar was not added, or the dish was cooked without the lid.",
                "symptom": "Cabbage has faded to a dull purple-grey"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "A splash of port added with the vinegar gives a more festive, richer flavour. For a vegan version, replace the butter with two tablespoons of olive oil. Orange zest stirred in at the end adds a citrus lift.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Braised red cabbage appears across northern and central European cooking. The German Rotkohl, Danish rodkal, and Austrian Blaukraut all share the same sweet-sour logic. The British version arrived with German and Dutch influence in the seventeenth century. Victorian cookery writer Mrs Beeton describes it straightforwardly as stewed red cabbage with vinegar and sugar.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
